## 8. Computer Science Foundations

These are not optional — they are the theoretical bedrock everything else is built on.

| Foundation | Relevance to Chttrix |
|---|---|
| **Data Structures** | Arrays, linked lists, hash maps, trees, heaps are used constantly — inside databases, state management, and routing tables |
| **Algorithms** | Sorting message lists, searching channels, pagination, autocomplete suggestions |
| **Operating Systems** | Understanding processes, threads, file systems, signals — explains why Node.js behaves as it does |
| **Computer Networks** | TCP/IP, DNS, HTTP, WebSockets — the transport layer for everything in this app |
| **System Design** | How to design scalable systems: choosing between SQL and NoSQL, designing APIs, choosing caching strategies |
| **Concurrency** | Node.js single-thread model; understanding race conditions, deadlocks, and how async I/O avoids blocking |
| **Cryptography basics** | How JWT signing works, what TLS does, how E2EE is implemented end-to-end |
| **Probability & Statistics** | Relevance scores, spam detection, AI feature evaluation (precision, recall) |
| **Linear Algebra** | Underlying math of ML models used in AI features (vector embeddings, similarity search) |

### Deep Dives Worth Pursuing

- **Hash maps:** Understanding O(1) lookup — the basis of in-memory caching, React's reconciliation algorithm, and database indexes.
- **B-Trees:** The data structure that powers database indexes in PostgreSQL.
- **CAP Theorem:** In a distributed system, you can only guarantee two of: Consistency, Availability, Partition Tolerance. This is why distributed databases make trade-offs.
- **TCP vs UDP:** Chat uses TCP (reliable, ordered); video calls often use UDP (fast, some loss acceptable).

